    <div class='content-main'>
      <div class="content-start">
        <h2><a name="authoring">Authoring Content</a></h2>
        <p>ACMS comes with default structured and unstructured content types. The structured content types are -</p>
        <p>
        <ol>
          <li>Places</li>
          <li>People</li>
          <li>Events</li>
          <li>Articles</li>
        </ol>
        </p>
        <p>Unstructured content types are -</p>
        <p>
        <ol>
          <li>Pages</li>
        </ol>
        </p>
        <p>You can use the pages content type to create any of the landing pages. The pages content type allows you to
          use the various Site Studio components and create landing pages as you like.
        </p>
        <p>The content types follow the out of the box content authoring experience. All you need to do is head over to
          the node/add screen and follow the links. For more detailed information please refer to the user guide.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="content-leaf">
        <h2><a name="editing">Editing and Publishing Content</a></h2>
        <p>ACMS comes with a pre-configured content lifecycle. An article or event (or any content type) begins with a
          draft state, moves to in review and finally gets published. Once you feel you no longer need the content for
          the site visitor you can move it to archive, which will unpublish the content from the site. Only content with
          state published is visible to site visitors. All other states are only visible to users with appropriate
          content permissions.
        </p>
        <p class="error">Please note the current workflow within ACMS is only set up for content types.</p>
        <div style="overflow-x:auto;">
          <table>
          <caption>Your site is pre-configured with the following roles:</caption>
          <thead>
          <th>Role</th>
          <th>Create</th>
          <th>Edit Own</th>
          <th>Edit Any</th>
          <th>Delete Own</th>
          <th>Delete Any</th>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
